otyped and marginalized roles—employed various strategies of cinematic and extracinematic performance to negotiate their complex positions in Hollywood and to ultimately “steal the show.” Drawing on a variety of source materials, Petty explores these stars’ reception among Black audiences and theorizes African American viewership in the early twentieth century. Her book is an important and welcome contribution to the literature on the movies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican American motion picture actors and actresseszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican Americans in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a1930s hollywood.  aafrican american actors.  aafrican american studies.  abill bojangles robinson.  abill robinson.  ablack actors steal the show.  ablack actors.  ablack studies.  abojangles.  acinematic performance for black actors.  aearly hollywood.  afilm studies.  afredi washington.  ahattie mcdaniel.  ahistory of film.  ahistory of hollywood.  alincoln perry.  alincoln stepin fetchit perry.  alouise beavers.  aproblematic stardom for black actors.  arace in early hollywood.  astepin fetchit.  astereotypical hollywood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052027975940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096414340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520964143423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520964143/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY